The course introduces the notion of discourse and its interdisciplinary application in different subfields of English Studies: linguistics, literature, culture studies and ELT. The course introduces argumentation techniques and discourses used in English-language texts as well as methods suitable for analyzing them. The course will cover both spoken and written texts in different subfields of English Studies, analyzing argumentation techniques, structural principles and cultural-ideological discourses used in the texts. The analysis of texts supports the development of students' skills of oral and written expression in English, but also critical reading and analysis skills necessary in conducting their own independent research.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course introduces the concept of discourse and the range of its applications in different subfields of English Studies (linguistics, literature, culture studies, language teaching). The course introduces argumentation techniques and discourses used in English-language texts as well as methods suitable for analyzing them. The course will cover both spoken and written texts in different subfields of English Studies. Students will read and analyze different text types, including academic research articles, honing their skills of critical reading necessary for their own independent research.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Students get an overview of the interdisciplinary possibilities of discourse analysis and are able to use its methods in their own research. After completing the course, students can recognize discourses prevalent in English-speaking cultures and can compare them to the Estonian ones. They acquire methods suitable for analyzing different English-language text types and the ability to apply them also in their own work. They also learn to critically analyze the uses of discourse analysis in scholarly literature. Students develop the skill of critical reading and text analysis, ability to work with English-language academic texts, skill of academic writing.
